l,"remark":"Siglar CO2 Contribution","total":-250.00000000000000000,"totalAccrued":-250.00000000000000000,"ws":null},{"accrual":100.00000000000000000,"displayOrder":3,"fixtureDisplayOrder":1,"flatRate":26000.00000000000000000,"isCommission":true,"name":"Demurrage","quantity":30.73923611111111000,"remark":null,"total":799220.13888888890000000,"totalAccrued":799220.13888888890000000,"ws":null}],"expenseList":[{"amount":2949.96000000000000000,"daily":false,"displayOrder":1,"fixtureDisplayOrder":1,"name":"Miscellaneous","remark":"Escort tugs DA / for SSSP","total":2949.96000000000000000},{"amount":1250.00000000000000000,"daily":false,"displayOrder":2,"fixtureDisplayOrder":1,"name":"Charterer\u2019s Expense","remark":"Gangway rental Houston","total":1250.00000000000000000},{"amount":12578.00000000000000000,"daily":false,"displayOrder":3,"fixtureDisplayOrder":1,"name":"Bunkers","remark":"Bunker Additives","total":12578.00000000000000000},{"amount":-16263.67000000000000000,"daily":false,"displayOrder":4,"fixtureDisplayOrder":1,"name":"Bunkers","remark":"Monjasa Settlement for offspec bunkers","total":-16263.67000000000000000}],"bunkerList":[{"averageConsumptionCost":401.05711620000000000,"bunkerGradeName":"LSBF","consCost":1045879.15398684000000000,"consTotal":2607.80600000000000000,"displayOrder":2,"refillPrice":395.00000000000000000,"remainderConsCost":0.00000000000000000,"totalCost":1045879.15398684000000000},{"averageConsumptionCost":391.38171358000000000,"bunkerGradeName":"LSGO","consCost":79009.40066562000000000,"consTotal":201.87300000000000000,"displayOrder":6,"refillPrice":445.00000000000000000,"remainderConsCost":0.00000000000000000,"totalCost":79009.40066562000000000}],"emissionsDetails":{"voyageCIIBand":null,"voyageCO2":null,"voyageEEOI":null,"voyageAER":null,"voyageSOxMt":null,"voyageSOx":null,"voyageNOxMt":null,"voyageNOx":null,"euEtsDetails":null,"legEmissionsDetails":[]},"remarkList":[{"modifiedDate":"2021-05-21T15:27:13.037","modifiedByFull":"Wright, Bryan","remark":"Operator comments: \n\t\n\tA challenge start to finish, we had few opportunities to catch our breaths on this one. Many of these numbers remain disputed, which I will explain in further detail below. \n\n         Alongside Enterprise Houston we took 1,900mt of VLSFO in three tanks (600/650/650). We were advised by Enterprise to keep the 600mt order separate from the 1,300mt as these were different specs. A few days after departing load port we were put on notice by owners for the 1,300mt parcel testing offspec for total sediment potential at four times the limit. Upon questioning the supplier it became clear they did not have a viable sample to use for testing. Despite instructing us to keep the bunkers segregated, suppliers had taken a composite sample for the entire 1,900mt parcel. We quickly booked additional bunkers in Trinidad and arranged for the vessel to offload tank by tank samples for further testing. Due to the long voyage to FEAST, lack of compatibility between future VLSFO stems, and two of our four bunker tanks unusable we knew this could be a major problem. We informed Vitol of anticipated delays and made every effort to expedite all operations. One day out from our bunkering Rendezvous point off Trinidad, AIS showed the bunker supplier had only recently departed the Panama Canal and would not arrive on time. We made the decision to cancel this stem and rebook off of Itaqui, Brazil since the supplier would be able to attend on arrival. \n         We arrived in Itaqui with one tank available for VLSFO. This small stem was enough to reach Port Elizabeth, but it was still necessary to cut into owner\u2019s safety Margin. A strong weather system to the East of Itaqui made for unsuitable conditions at the offshore bunkering area. After multiple days waiting for the weather to improve, the supplying vessel was forced into port for crew change and provisions. By the time we sailed, nine days had been lost on this bunkering. Suppliers later advised they had never experienced such delays, but considering the vulnerability in that part of the world I would recommend our ops team avoid it in the future. \n         Upon departing Itaqui, we treated the offspec fuel with additives and began trials in the auxiliary engines. If this had worked a Port Elizabeth bunkering would not be necessary, but the additives did not stabilize the fuel to owner\u2019s satisfaction.\nWe sailed to Port Elizabeth for next bunkering with an agreement from owners to comingle the new VLSFO and Itaqui VLSFO in small ratios. We were able to take enough now to reach Singapore and limited the bunkering call to 14 hours. We purchased new additives and began trials again in Auxiliary Engines. We did not have approval to burn the Houston bunkers in Main Engines until after we left Singapore, but to date, we have now consumed almost 850mt with about 415mt left on board. \n         If the Houston fuel had been on spec, the bunkering in Itaqui would not have been necessary. As a result we arrived three days late for charterer\u2019s discharge window. The vessel was instructed to wait OPL Singapore for the next berthing window four weeks later. Vitol has put us on notice for this waiting time. \n         The master tendered NOR at EOPL, but did not issue a letter of protest when Free Pratique was not granted after six hours. The charter party for this fixture is BPVoy4, which essentially renders our NOR invalid if there is no FP or LOP for the same. \n         While waiting for berthing at EOPL the vessel was detained by Malaysian authorities, charged with entering Malaysian waters. This took 3-4 days to resolve and resulted in the owners paying a $25k fine. Had charterers been informed, this would also invalidate our NOR. Control of these waters is heavily disputed between Malaysia, Indonesia, and Singapore. Note to ops - keep an eye on our vessels waiting at EOPL and ensure they wait closer to the Horsburgh lighthouse to the South and min 20nm from Malaysia.\n         All this to say, our demurrage claim is exposed from several angles. If Vitol makes the argument for unlawful deviations for bunkering, we feel we have a decent position to reject their claim. If Vitol claims our NOR is invalid without FP or an LOP they will likely win. In this case the lost time can be claimed back from owners. If an argument is made based on the arrest of the vessel, it would be difficult to claim from the owners or charterers.\n         One question we have raised several times, is how much of these costs could be passed on to the bunker suppliers? In short, the contract with Monjasa leaves them in a very good position with no liability for deviations, lost demurrage, etc. We have claimed them for the additional bunkering time and additives, but of the $212k USD claim, I am only confident in recovery of about $30k. This has not been included in the above calculation.\n         Aside from the above, the voyage was mostly in line with estimates. Differences as follows.\n-\tLoading Houston instead of Corpus Christi saves ~ $30k in port costs\n-\tSingapore port costs $15k less than estimated\n-\tTopping off cargo via STS invoiced as interim port for ~ $90k\n-\tFreight billed as estimated\n-\t39 more laden days due to Itaqui bunkering and month long waiting period for discharge at Singapore\n-\tVLSFO $18/mt more expensive than estimated (this was in the middle of the massive bunker price spike earlier this year)\n-\t$12k for bunker additives, which will likely be rebilled to Monjasa\n\n\tImprovements: \n\t\n-\tA reminder to ops, continue including NOR tendering instructions in fixture information \u2013 this is much easier than remembering to look for a separate email when many NORs are tendered at the beginning of a midnight laycan.  \n-\tI do not recommend bunkering offshore Itaqui, but good to know it is there in an emergency\n-\tWe ran into an issue where the vessel did not witness bunker surveyors\u2019 samples, and the surveyors did not witness the crew taking samples. We should discuss including something in instructions to the master to limit doubt in sample testing.\n-\tIvan from Prolquid was very helpful in debunkering conversations if you find yourself in that position. ops@pro-liquid.com"}],"offhireList":[],"tcNumber":null,"tcOutIdEncrypted":null,"tcReletDetail":null}